functional. We don't write hits. Now don't get me wrong, I have nothing against hits.

37
00:02:34,670 --> 00:02:38,113
I would love to have a hit. I think it's a great thing to shoot for. It's just not what we do.

38
00:02:38,633 --> 00:02:45,981
We try to service a respectable niche with competent games in order to sustain a pleasant,

39
00:02:46,161 --> 00:02:50,345
sustainable middle-class income. So why am I up here?

40
00:02:52,318 --> 00:02:55,439
Indie developers love and should love postmortems.

41
00:02:55,479 --> 00:02:57,399
They love the stories of creating a thing,

42
00:02:57,439 --> 00:02:59,480
because you can sort of pick through it magpie-like

43
00:02:59,800 --> 00:03:01,320
and look for elements of the story

44
00:03:01,360 --> 00:03:02,761
that you can use to help yourself.

45
00:03:03,061 --> 00:03:04,881
Well, this is a postmortem, too, except it's not

46
00:03:04,921 --> 00:03:07,122
a postmortem of a game, but of a career,

47
00:03:07,962 --> 00:03:11,123
because I am older than the stones and the dirt.

48
00:03:11,143 --> 00:03:15,004
I have been writing indie games continuously for a living

49
00:03:15,224 --> 00:03:18,305
longer than, I'm not going to say everyone.

50
00:03:18,852 --> 00:03:24,094
but the list of people who have been doing it longer is not long and it's by a matter of months.

51
00:03:26,456 --> 00:03:34,000
Indie games as a big thing are new. They're really new. We only became a full big hundred

52
00:03:34,040 --> 00:03:37,922
million dollar a year industry in like the last five or six years. So the idea of how to do a

53
00:03:38,202 --> 00:03:44,365
full career, a 20, 30, 40 year career in this industry is very much an open question. So it's

54
00:03:44,385 --> 00:03:48,267
not talked about much. 40 years, my god, there isn't going to be a planet left then.

55
00:03:48,902 --> 00:03:51,984
So that's why, that's the purpose of this talk,

56
00:03:52,024 --> 00:03:53,865
to start approaching this question.

57
00:03:53,905 --> 00:03:55,487
How do you keep the ball rolling?

58
00:03:55,947 --> 00:04:00,270
And so I'm gonna tell you a story about the last 25 years,

59
00:04:00,290 --> 00:04:02,452
a couple lame funny anecdotes,

60
00:04:02,912 --> 00:04:05,594
and a couple things that I've observed

61
00:04:05,654 --> 00:04:06,935
about the nature of our industry.

62
00:04:07,695 --> 00:04:10,057
I'm not gonna have any answers for anybody

63
00:04:10,077 --> 00:04:11,718
because you're all your own artists.

64
00:04:12,039 --> 00:04:14,600
But perhaps some things I say might help you

65
00:04:14,640 --> 00:04:16,142
to ask a better quality of question.

66
00:04:22,248 --> 00:04:27,950
So this is the old person part of the talk and I've observed that there is nothing that

67
00:04:28,350 --> 00:04:34,753
young people hate more than old people talking about what things were like when the world

68
00:04:34,813 --> 00:04:35,153
was young.

69
00:04:35,333 --> 00:04:36,854
Who punched cards?

70
00:04:38,855 --> 00:04:42,836
My first computer was a cinder block with a keyboard duct tape to it.

71
00:04:43,277 --> 00:04:46,158
Yeah, there's going to be there's going to be a tiny bit of that, but I promised to try

72
00:04:46,178 --> 00:04:49,419
to round it around to some bring it around to something that might be valuable to you.

73
00:04:50,089 --> 00:04:51,069
So how did I get started?

74
00:04:51,349 --> 00:04:53,311
I was a really, really weird kid.

75
00:04:54,511 --> 00:04:57,053
When I was five, I spent all of my time

76
00:04:57,273 --> 00:04:58,874
in my bedroom with a pencil and paper

77
00:04:58,894 --> 00:05:01,116
drawing increasingly elaborate mazes

78
00:05:01,196 --> 00:05:02,376
because they fascinated me.

79
00:05:02,717 --> 00:05:05,318
I was lucky enough to have worried but basically

80
00:05:05,398 --> 00:05:09,181
supportive parents.

81
00:05:09,301 --> 00:05:11,582
1975 or so, my dad went to a bar with friends,

82
00:05:11,682 --> 00:05:12,783
and he came home and said, Jeff, I

83
00:05:12,823 --> 00:05:14,544
saw this weird thing I'd never seen before.

84
00:05:14,564 --> 00:05:15,565
I thought you'd find it interesting.

85
00:05:15,945 --> 00:05:18,967
And he described to me a thing called Pong.

86
00:05:19,695 --> 00:05:21,757
And he was right, it did sound awful interesting.

87
00:05:21,837 --> 00:05:24,098
But I couldn't try it because even in 1975,

88
00:05:24,718 --> 00:05:27,359
five-year-olds hanging out in bars was not going to fly.

89
00:05:28,060 --> 00:05:30,561
But one year later, on a Washington State ferry,

90
00:05:30,621 --> 00:05:32,922
I found this big old wooden box where

91
00:05:32,942 --> 00:05:34,243
you could put a quarter in the front

92
00:05:34,643 --> 00:05:36,965
and you could fire rectangular torpedoes

93
00:05:37,225 --> 00:05:39,126
at these two-dimensional boats for 70 seconds.

94
00:05:39,146 --> 00:05:40,847
And if you did it really well, you

95
00:05:40,887 --> 00:05:42,207
could do it for 20 more seconds.

96
00:05:42,588 --> 00:05:47,250
And even then, my tiny little barely alive pea brain

97
00:05:47,330 --> 00:05:48,631
knew that this.

98
00:05:49,440 --> 00:05:51,662
was my thing. This was my bag.

99
00:05:52,723 --> 00:05:54,345
Writing video games for a living

100
00:05:54,925 --> 00:05:56,987
was an idea that compelled me all through my childhood.

101
00:05:57,007 --> 00:05:59,029
All through, I read everything I could about video games,

102
00:05:59,069 --> 00:06:01,412
about programming, I played them whenever I got the chance.

103
00:06:02,553 --> 00:06:06,096
When I was 10, I walked into my fourth-grade classroom

104
00:06:06,256 --> 00:06:08,418
and there were people with this weird-looking blue book

105
00:06:08,459 --> 00:06:09,520
and some funny-shaped dice.

106
00:06:09,660 --> 00:06:12,342
And once again, I didn't look at it for like two or three seconds

107
00:06:12,362 --> 00:06:14,004
before it had colonized my brain.

108
00:06:14,467 --> 00:06:18,009
And that night, I was bugging my parents, please, oh my god,

109
00:06:18,029 --> 00:06:19,631
take me to the mall so I can buy this.

110
00:06:20,511 --> 00:06:23,133
And that was how I got started with Dungeons and Dragons.

111
00:06:24,174 --> 00:06:26,576
My school library had a program where kids could write books.

112
00:06:26,596 --> 00:06:27,877
And you could put them in the school library,

113
00:06:27,897 --> 00:06:29,158
and then other kids could check them out.

114
00:06:29,578 --> 00:06:32,601
And so I immediately had to learn to type, hunt, and text

115
00:06:32,621 --> 00:06:35,843
style, and I wrote my first D&D module, put it in the library.

116
00:06:36,324 --> 00:06:38,866
Now, the news media at the time, even the most prestigious

117
00:06:39,026 --> 00:06:40,467
outlets, was starting to run stories

118
00:06:40,607 --> 00:06:42,168
about the evil of gamers.

119
00:06:42,631 --> 00:06:49,575
about how there are these treacherous, evil, corrupt, insidious creatures who must be feared

120
00:06:50,035 --> 00:06:55,899
a proud media tradition that continues to this day and as a result a concerned parent

121
00:06:55,939 --> 00:07:00,001
called the school library and as a result of that I am the only person I know personally

122
00:07:00,041 --> 00:07:07,085
who has had a book banned from a school library. This is the module that I wrote, art also

123
00:07:07,145 --> 00:07:07,465
by me.

124
00:07:08,035 --> 00:07:11,998
the tunnels of Grok, and you will note in the title that I spell the tunnels with the

125
00:07:12,058 --> 00:07:13,920
somewhat less common L-E spelling.

126
00:07:16,502 --> 00:07:17,342
What was the point of all that?

127
00:07:19,304 --> 00:07:25,068
I have been gifted with a gift that is almost unprecedented in the whole of human experience.

128
00:07:25,968 --> 00:07:30,051
I am older than the art form in which I work.

129
00:07:30,932 --> 00:07:34,655
Now, this is one of my all-time favorite quotes by William Goldman, writer and screenwriter

130
00:07:34,675 --> 00:07:36,316
best known for making The Princess Bride.

131
00:07:37,484 --> 00:07:38,685
Nobody knows anything.

132
00:07:38,905 --> 00:07:40,706
And he was saying this about the film industry, which

133
00:07:40,746 --> 00:07:43,707
is a far better understood industry than ours.

134
00:07:45,088 --> 00:07:46,308
Video games are young.

135
00:07:46,829 --> 00:07:47,869
Nobody knows anything.

136
00:07:47,909 --> 00:07:49,350
We're still scrambling to figure out,

137
00:07:49,550 --> 00:07:50,570
how do we design these things?

138
00:07:50,731 --> 00:07:51,611
How do we create these things?

139
00:07:51,731 --> 00:07:52,571
How do we test these things?

140
00:07:52,711 --> 00:07:53,732
How do we sell these things?

141
00:07:53,892 --> 00:07:54,772
How do we market these things?

142
00:07:54,953 --> 00:07:57,454
How do we add loot boxes to a $100 million project

143
00:07:57,494 --> 00:07:59,795
without causing it to blow up on the launch pad?

144
00:08:01,476 --> 00:08:02,896
Nobody knows anything.

145
00:08:02,956 --> 00:08:04,457
And if you think you know a rule,

146
00:08:04,855 --> 00:08:08,736
one of you out there, your fortune and your fame might be figuring out the way to break that rule.

147
00:08:09,377 --> 00:08:13,978
And, you know, in two days, grown-up GBC is going to start. Real GBC is going to start.

148
00:08:14,178 --> 00:08:17,599
And these halls are going to be filled with Microsoft people, Electronic Arts people,

149
00:08:17,639 --> 00:08:21,380
and Activision people walking down the hall like they're too cool for school,

150
00:08:21,440 --> 00:08:24,340
and looking at me like there's something they just scraped off their shoe.

151
00:08:24,661 --> 00:08:28,562
And there's going to be high-powered consultants here whose job is to charge a fortune to stand

152
00:08:28,602 --> 00:08:31,562
in the corner of the room and pretend they're the person who knows something.

153
00:08:32,463 --> 00:08:33,283
Don't be fooled.

154
00:08:34,302 --> 00:08:37,924
Nobody knows anything, and this is your art form just as much as theirs.

155
00:08:39,125 --> 00:08:39,385
Sue.

156
00:08:44,708 --> 00:08:45,628
Don't patronize me.

157
00:08:46,069 --> 00:08:46,489
Okay.

158
00:08:48,510 --> 00:08:52,973
My first game was a thing called Shareware, which was a marketing technique.

159
00:08:53,413 --> 00:08:54,293
What was Shareware?

160
00:08:54,673 --> 00:09:00,036
Well, in 1994, most software was sold in boxes on store shelves, and Shareware is based on

161
00:09:00,076 --> 00:09:02,518
the bananas radical idea.

162
00:09:03,020 --> 00:09:06,584
Wait a second, what we're going to do is we're going to write demos of our games, small portions,

163
00:09:07,624 --> 00:09:11,608
and people are free to spread their demos to everyone that they knew.

164
00:09:11,788 --> 00:09:14,570
They could put them up on BBSs, they could put them on Americana Online, they could give

165
00:09:14,630 --> 00:09:18,113
copies of the demos to their friends in the off chance they had any.

166
00:09:18,794 --> 00:09:23,558
And if you liked the demo, then you, OK, you pirated it 90% of the time.

167
00:09:23,738 --> 00:09:27,562
But sometimes you've got the full version by sending me money.

168
00:09:28,322 --> 00:09:28,442
Now...

169
00:09:29,452 --> 00:09:34,514
How did you these demos get around and how did the money come back because bear in mind at this time.

170
00:09:35,434 --> 00:09:39,656
There wasn't really an Internet this is we're back to 1994.

171
00:09:41,716 --> 00:09:54,922
There was no real web browser there was no real web most people this is my first 14 4K modem which was capable of downloading my 1.2 megabyte first game demo in a blazing 90 minutes.

172
00:09:57,022 --> 00:09:57,603
You used these.

173
00:09:59,556 --> 00:10:00,757
How was your game distributed?

174
00:10:01,337 --> 00:10:04,299
Well, you could put your demo on AOL, CompuServe, Prodigy.

175
00:10:04,339 --> 00:10:06,860
These were services that cost $3 an hour to be on.

176
00:10:07,080 --> 00:10:10,262
That's how much the internet cost in 1994, $3 an hour.

177
00:10:12,284 --> 00:10:14,905
You could get demos by buying magazines, which

178
00:10:14,945 --> 00:10:17,126
have shareware on disks in the front.

179
00:10:18,107 --> 00:10:20,789
You could go to your local OfficeMax or CompUSA

180
00:10:21,189 --> 00:10:23,950
and spend $10 for a disk with 30 to 200 shareware demos

181
00:10:24,031 --> 00:10:24,791
to try out.

182
00:10:25,511 --> 00:10:25,772
Excuse me.

183
00:10:29,380 --> 00:10:30,842
You want a discoverability problem.

184
00:10:31,142 --> 00:10:32,964
This is a discoverability problem.

185
00:10:33,664 --> 00:10:37,187
And finally, my favorite, you could go to the mall,

186
00:10:37,367 --> 00:10:39,709
and you could go to kiosks, and you could go to shops,

187
00:10:40,030 --> 00:10:42,472
and then there were walls covered with disks

188
00:10:42,612 --> 00:10:43,973
with shareware demos on them.

189
00:10:44,333 --> 00:10:47,256
So you would go, and you would pay up to $10

190
00:10:47,336 --> 00:10:48,217
for a shareware demo.

191
00:10:48,617 --> 00:10:50,279
You would take it home, you'd put it on your computer,

192
00:10:50,579 --> 00:10:51,540
and if you liked it.

193
00:10:52,071 --> 00:10:54,412
You would call me on the phone and say, hey, I got your demo.

194
00:10:54,452 --> 00:10:55,152
I want the full game.

195
00:10:55,212 --> 00:10:57,013
I'd say, hey, the full game is $25.

196
00:10:57,433 --> 00:11:00,415
And then you would say, you freaking con artist,

197
00:11:00,515 --> 00:11:02,015
I paid $10 for this disc.

198
00:11:02,295 --> 00:11:04,857
And then proceed to yell at me for upwards of five hours.

199
00:11:06,998 --> 00:11:08,718
So as you liked the game, you wanted to send money back.

200
00:11:09,118 --> 00:11:11,720
You mailed me a check using a stamp.

201
00:11:12,440 --> 00:11:15,021
You would get a postal money order from the post office.

202
00:11:15,241 --> 00:11:16,342
You would mail me cash.

203
00:11:16,622 --> 00:11:19,803
One Viking mailed me $25 in change.

204
00:11:20,083 --> 00:11:20,804
The envelope went like this.

205
00:11:20,924 --> 00:11:21,924
Ching, ching, ching, ching.

206
00:11:22,716 --> 00:11:25,539
And finally, if you could get a credit card, a bank to trust you,

207
00:11:25,579 --> 00:11:27,981
your small business could gain the ability to accept credit cards,

208
00:11:28,041 --> 00:11:29,082
which almost never happened.

209
00:11:29,122 --> 00:11:30,883
Put a pin in that. I'll get back to that later.

210
00:11:31,704 --> 00:11:34,867
So, it's 1994. I'm in grad school, and I hate it.

211
00:11:34,967 --> 00:11:37,549
My wife at the time has already quit grad school

212
00:11:38,050 --> 00:11:41,273
and gotten a real job, and we decide to live the dream

213
00:11:41,333 --> 00:11:43,134
and actually own a computer.

214
00:11:44,135 --> 00:11:45,476
I will, as an aside at this point,

215
00:11:46,083 --> 00:11:50,925
I have been very lucky in my life in the opportunities I've been given and the background that I

216
00:11:50,965 --> 00:11:53,806
have that just enabled me to learn to program when I was a child.

217
00:11:54,206 --> 00:11:56,827
I want to make it very clear that that fact has not escaped me.

218
00:11:58,268 --> 00:12:02,209
Now here's your standard old person statistics for our first computer which cost about $3,700

219
00:12:03,669 --> 00:12:06,310
of today dollars adjusted for inflation.

220
00:12:06,330 --> 00:12:11,952
It came with 8 megabytes of RAM which could be upgraded to a lofty and princely 16 megabytes

221
00:12:11,992 --> 00:12:12,812
for only $680 of today dollars.

222
00:12:14,539 --> 00:12:18,002
I bought Code Warrior to write computer programs because I liked doing that.

223
00:12:18,162 --> 00:12:21,485
And if you wanted to learn to program at the time, there was no Internet, so there were

224
00:12:21,505 --> 00:12:22,306
no discussion groups.

225
00:12:22,526 --> 00:12:25,709
You just went to the local bookstore, you bought books, and you stared at them until

226
00:12:25,749 --> 00:12:28,031
little pinpricks of blood started appearing on your forehead.

227
00:12:30,052 --> 00:12:30,573
Got a computer.

228
00:12:30,793 --> 00:12:32,795
I want to play a role-playing game because that's totally my bag.

229
00:12:33,055 --> 00:12:33,976
But I couldn't find any.

230
00:12:35,237 --> 00:12:37,198
So I figure, what the hell?

231
00:12:37,619 --> 00:12:38,800
There's no role-playing games.

232
00:12:39,040 --> 00:12:40,001
I might as well write one.

233
00:12:40,261 --> 00:12:42,943
And if there had been good role-playing games at the time, I probably never would have written

234
00:12:43,023 --> 00:12:43,103
one.

235
00:12:43,648 --> 00:12:45,529
But I just happened to get another lucky break.

236
00:12:45,810 --> 00:12:46,850
You're going to see this chart again.

