00:12:51,332 --> 00:12:55,134
have a tendency to go through boom times and bust times.

240
00:12:55,475 --> 00:12:57,536
It is a very important concept to understand.

241
00:12:57,576 --> 00:12:59,276
I'll get back to it when I talk about today.

242
00:12:59,296 --> 00:13:01,358
I grad school.

243
00:13:01,798 --> 00:13:03,299
I can live my lifelong dream.

244
00:13:03,459 --> 00:13:04,579
I'm going to sit down, and I'm going

245
00:13:04,619 --> 00:13:06,460
to write a full-length fantasy role-playing game

246
00:13:06,840 --> 00:13:07,981
and, what the hell, release it to try

247
00:13:08,001 --> 00:13:08,881
to get some pizza money.

248
00:13:09,982 --> 00:13:12,743
So now I've got to sit in a room and stare at the wall.

249
00:13:13,678 --> 00:13:14,639
What the heck am I going to do?

250
00:13:14,879 --> 00:13:16,839
I'm going to live my dream, but what am I going to write?

251
00:13:16,879 --> 00:13:17,559
How am I going to write it?

252
00:13:18,320 --> 00:13:19,740
So it doesn't take me long.

253
00:13:19,860 --> 00:13:20,580
I come up with the idea.

254
00:13:20,620 --> 00:13:21,720
I loved these games as a kid.

255
00:13:22,181 --> 00:13:23,101
So what I'm going to do is I'm going

256
00:13:23,121 --> 00:13:24,821
to go to every single game I liked as a kid

257
00:13:25,041 --> 00:13:27,262
and steal the single best idea from every one.

258
00:13:28,142 --> 00:13:29,602
And I'm going to, in my craftsman way,

259
00:13:29,622 --> 00:13:34,083
amalgamate them into what I hope is a cohesive and satisfying

260
00:13:34,103 --> 00:13:34,363
whole.

261
00:13:36,127 --> 00:13:37,407
Indie games are great for innovation.

262
00:13:37,788 --> 00:13:40,249
I love innovation, but innovation is not the only path.

263
00:13:40,269 --> 00:13:42,071
You must remember that every single one of us

264
00:13:42,131 --> 00:13:43,632
stands on the shoulders of giants.

265
00:13:46,334 --> 00:13:49,496
I looked at what I liked to play, and then I copied it.

266
00:13:50,297 --> 00:13:51,617
That is my creative process.

267
00:13:51,657 --> 00:13:54,039
And my second lesson is, this is all gonna be about

268
00:13:54,259 --> 00:13:57,021
finding my creative process, my way of doing business,

269
00:13:57,101 --> 00:13:58,282
and the importance of defending it.

270
00:13:58,642 --> 00:14:01,124
And this is gonna sound like sort of artsy-fartsy,

271
00:14:01,404 --> 00:14:03,686
ooh, follow your bliss, man, advice.

272
00:14:04,166 --> 00:14:04,627
No, it's not.

273
00:14:05,529 --> 00:14:08,570
It's very hard-nosed practical advice, and I'll tell you why.

274
00:14:09,231 --> 00:14:12,172
Most of the people you're going to run into in this thing

275
00:14:12,252 --> 00:14:15,293
are looking at their career over a time frame of one year, two

276
00:14:15,313 --> 00:14:17,394
years, five years, which is reasonable, especially

277
00:14:17,414 --> 00:14:18,235
if you're trying to get started.

278
00:14:18,435 --> 00:14:19,935
But that's not the time frame I think in.

279
00:14:20,415 --> 00:14:23,717
I'm thinking about in 20 years, in 10 years, in 40 years.

280
00:14:24,177 --> 00:14:27,238
I want to know what your career writing shareware games is

281
00:14:27,258 --> 00:14:30,020
going to be like in 40 years.

282
00:14:31,600 --> 00:14:33,041
And that's a long time.

283
00:14:33,511 --> 00:15:03,324
If you're going to work in that length of time and you're going to be operating at a very peak level of efficiency because you need to in this business you need to create a life you need to create a mindset you need to create a process that is not going to rub you because if you if there's something that's rubbing at you if there's something that's putting you off your feed over the next 40 years it is going to rub you down to a nub. So. I'm writing a game I do my grad school stuff during the day and I work on the game at night.

284
00:15:03,674 --> 00:15:06,817
Fortunately, I was in my 20s, so I had infinite energy.

285
00:15:07,397 --> 00:15:10,059
I spent four months hacking out something like an engine.

286
00:15:10,380 --> 00:15:12,381
My wife at the time was enormously supportive.

287
00:15:12,421 --> 00:15:16,405
She drew these adorable little cartoon graphic icons for me

288
00:15:16,885 --> 00:15:19,147
that I still get emails requesting to this day.

289
00:15:20,608 --> 00:15:22,490
I spent about five minutes making the world, placing

290
00:15:22,510 --> 00:15:25,272
the walls, placing the swords, giving the orcs dialogue,

291
00:15:25,492 --> 00:15:26,473
another month testing it.

292
00:15:27,734 --> 00:15:28,635
And then it was done.

293
00:15:28,955 --> 00:15:31,517
I had a complete functional.

294
00:15:32,332 --> 00:15:35,453
massively, massively flawed whole.

295
00:15:35,813 --> 00:15:37,854
But I had something I could hand to people and say,

296
00:15:37,894 --> 00:15:38,694
this, see this?

297
00:15:38,974 --> 00:15:40,755
This is a game.

298
00:15:50,278 --> 00:15:51,318
It was massively flawed.

299
00:15:51,898 --> 00:15:53,179
It embarrassed me deeply.

300
00:15:53,239 --> 00:15:55,139
But then again, every product I ever write

301
00:15:55,760 --> 00:15:56,700
embarrasses me deeply.

302
00:15:58,547 --> 00:16:02,530
This is one of my guiding phrases when working this business.

303
00:16:02,670 --> 00:16:06,813
In the end, you struggle to ship the game,

304
00:16:06,833 --> 00:16:08,154
but at some point, you've got to push the button.

305
00:16:08,174 --> 00:16:10,036
At some point, you've got to kick the thing out the door.

306
00:16:10,396 --> 00:16:13,318
If I double the amount of time working on a game seeking perfection,

307
00:16:13,378 --> 00:16:16,460
I need to double the amount of sales that I get from that game to justify it.

308
00:16:16,821 --> 00:16:18,342
Doubling your sales is hard.

309
00:16:19,262 --> 00:16:21,204
Time is valuable.

310
00:16:21,804 --> 00:16:24,846
I am always striving to be the only thing better than good, which

311
00:16:24,926 --> 00:16:25,787
is good enough.

312
00:16:27,343 --> 00:16:28,324
I get another lucky break.

313
00:16:28,464 --> 00:16:31,565
I'm on Usenet, which is the only discussion forum

314
00:16:31,585 --> 00:16:32,066
on the internet.

315
00:16:32,086 --> 00:16:33,786
At this time, the internet was small enough

316
00:16:33,806 --> 00:16:37,308
that only one insane, anarchic discussion board

317
00:16:37,508 --> 00:16:38,488
covers the whole thing.

318
00:16:38,989 --> 00:16:40,970
The Fandasoft had a hit game called Realms,

319
00:16:40,990 --> 00:16:42,050
and they wanted to get in publishing.

320
00:16:42,070 --> 00:16:43,731
So they offered me a really good deal

321
00:16:43,791 --> 00:16:45,211
in order to take my orders for me

322
00:16:45,291 --> 00:16:48,113
and give me sort of a basis of a couple thousand people

323
00:16:48,133 --> 00:16:49,093
to tell about my game.

324
00:16:49,773 --> 00:16:51,434
They were enormously helpful to me.

325
00:16:51,474 --> 00:16:52,915
I probably would not have a business

326
00:16:52,955 --> 00:16:53,815
if it wasn't for their help.

327
00:16:54,876 --> 00:16:59,857
Third lesson, I strongly recommend whenever possible that you be lucky.

328
00:16:59,877 --> 00:17:02,298
I tend to get in a lot of trouble when I say this.

329
00:17:02,358 --> 00:17:05,999
There are a lot of people who, just to get through the day, they really need to believe

330
00:17:06,059 --> 00:17:10,240
that they live in a deterministic world that contains some measure of justice.

331
00:17:10,660 --> 00:17:13,581
But that is not the case, especially when you're trying to live in art.

332
00:17:13,641 --> 00:17:15,301
You eventually are going to need a lucky break.

333
00:17:15,321 --> 00:17:17,242
Eventually you're going to need someone to vouch for you.

334
00:17:18,022 --> 00:17:23,863
And all you can do until that time is work your butt off so that when your lucky break

335
00:17:24,023 --> 00:17:24,363
comes.

336
00:17:24,893 --> 00:17:27,635
you are fully ready to jump on it and take advantage of it.

337
00:17:28,835 --> 00:17:29,516
Some starting games.

338
00:17:29,536 --> 00:17:31,877
I have to do all the tedious legal business stuff.

339
00:17:31,897 --> 00:17:33,938
I have to research what it takes to get a business license

340
00:17:34,098 --> 00:17:35,239
and then do that.

341
00:17:35,739 --> 00:17:37,640
Pick a business name, all of that stuff.

342
00:17:38,000 --> 00:17:43,023
So my next bit of advice, have a quality accountant.

343
00:17:43,543 --> 00:17:46,284
And I know you're thinking, this is a professional conference.

344
00:17:46,324 --> 00:17:48,605
Why are you telling me this tedious one-on-one level stuff?

345
00:17:48,867 --> 00:17:54,150
because I have lost count of the times when I've talked to a seasoned independent professional

346
00:17:54,190 --> 00:17:59,815
who should know better and they're asking me questions and I'm like, dude, you need

347
00:17:59,855 --> 00:18:02,136
an accountant, not me.

348
00:18:02,597 --> 00:18:06,339
Because once you get to the point where you need to pay taxes, where you need to do payroll,

349
00:18:06,800 --> 00:18:10,162
the mistakes are many and they are high impact.

350
00:18:10,502 --> 00:18:12,804
If you screw up your payroll withholding.

351
00:18:13,250 --> 00:18:18,635
All that is going to earn you is a tiny little sympathetic shake of the head from your auditor

352
00:18:18,835 --> 00:18:21,177
before he destroys you.

353
00:18:21,197 --> 00:18:28,644
I'm selling a game, so I need to pick a price which is as difficult back then as it is now.

354
00:18:28,984 --> 00:18:32,787
Fortunately, at the time, all successful shareware games were $25, so I picked that.

355
00:18:33,168 --> 00:18:34,349
That is, in today dollars, $41.

356
00:18:34,829 --> 00:18:35,910
Now imagine that.

357
00:18:36,371 --> 00:18:38,893
Imagine actually being able to look people straight in the eyes and charge them $41 for

358
00:18:38,953 --> 00:18:39,153
a game.

359
00:18:40,669 --> 00:18:46,532
But the tragic truth of it is that we are making a bespoke artisanal product for a niche market,

360
00:18:46,552 --> 00:18:47,832
and we should be able to charge this.

361
00:18:47,872 --> 00:18:50,974
It is only the overcrowding that keeps us from being able to charge what we're worth.

362
00:18:51,774 --> 00:18:53,235
But that's the tragedy of the business.

363
00:18:54,356 --> 00:18:56,036
Shareware, so I have to make a demo.

364
00:18:56,157 --> 00:18:59,498
And another tragedy of my business is that I always make my demos too big.

365
00:18:59,758 --> 00:19:00,419
10 hours, 20 hours.

366
00:19:00,519 --> 00:19:03,360
I released a game with like a 30-hour demo.

367
00:19:03,860 --> 00:19:08,343
I shudder to think of the amount of money that that insanity cost me over the years.

368
00:19:08,966 --> 00:19:11,688
But I've always been weirdly, weirdly proud of it, too.

369
00:19:13,389 --> 00:19:14,430
One thing that helped me sleep at night

370
00:19:14,450 --> 00:19:16,371
is that pretty much everyone who got my game, one,

371
00:19:16,572 --> 00:19:18,173
tried it and found it worked on their computer,

372
00:19:18,193 --> 00:19:20,655
two, played it enough to know they enjoy it.

373
00:19:21,055 --> 00:19:22,696
And since we're indie developers and we

374
00:19:22,736 --> 00:19:24,457
like to act like we are subscribed

375
00:19:24,497 --> 00:19:27,440
to a higher ethical standard, one of my mottos

376
00:19:27,480 --> 00:19:29,061
has always been, look, if you don't like my game,

377
00:19:29,141 --> 00:19:30,182
I don't want your money.

378
00:19:30,562 --> 00:19:31,723
I'm going to be the only person you're

379
00:19:31,743 --> 00:19:32,844
going to run into in this thing who

380
00:19:32,864 --> 00:19:35,366
think the main problem with the Steam's refund policies

381
00:19:35,386 --> 00:19:36,747
is that they're not generous enough.

382
00:19:37,221 --> 00:19:40,564
I've had a one year no questions asked refund policy forever,

383
00:19:40,824 --> 00:19:41,905
and I've never had problems with it.

384
00:19:41,925 --> 00:19:45,528
Because by and large, the people who pay money for games

385
00:19:45,588 --> 00:19:46,289
are pretty honest.

386
00:19:47,890 --> 00:19:49,752
It's done, and I'm out of excuses.

387
00:19:50,433 --> 00:19:51,894
It's time for me to press the button

388
00:19:51,934 --> 00:19:54,516
to upload the demo to America Online

389
00:19:55,137 --> 00:19:58,300
and change my life forever.

390
00:19:58,960 --> 00:19:59,821
And I'm terrified.

391
00:20:00,101 --> 00:20:01,202
I'm completely terrified.

392
00:20:01,262 --> 00:20:02,663
And I'm only able to do it by making

393
00:20:02,703 --> 00:20:04,725
what I call a progressive screwdriver.

394
00:20:05,152 --> 00:20:06,713
And here is how you make that.

395
00:20:06,953 --> 00:20:08,393
A screwdriver is an alcoholic beverage.

396
00:20:08,433 --> 00:20:10,194
It is orange juice with vodka added.

397
00:20:10,454 --> 00:20:11,894
If I just made a screwdriver, drank it down,

398
00:20:11,954 --> 00:20:13,434
and then just added more vodka.

399
00:20:15,195 --> 00:20:17,536
When I pressed the upload for my first game,

400
00:20:18,116 --> 00:20:20,656
I was wasted.

401
00:20:26,098 --> 00:20:27,338
And God help me, it sold.

402
00:20:27,678 --> 00:20:31,079
We got a little core of people buying the game

403
00:20:31,399 --> 00:20:32,520
because of our publisher.

404
00:20:33,363 --> 00:20:37,764
we because of that attention we got probably the one of the single biggest stroke of luck

405
00:20:37,944 --> 00:20:43,145
a copy of Macworld put us on their shareware CD which was enormously successful and because

406
00:20:43,425 --> 00:20:49,667
our game just it was there weren't many role-playing games and ours was competent we got a lot of word

407
00:20:49,687 --> 00:20:54,028
of mouth and a lot of people say don't count on word of mouth don't count on word of word

408
00:20:54,048 --> 00:20:58,229
of mouth isn't going to get you through and i'm like i've always been reading it like good lord

409
00:20:58,589 --> 00:20:59,850
what else do i have

410
00:21:00,823 --> 00:21:02,124
My games are slow-paced.

411
00:21:02,144 --> 00:21:04,125
They're not good for YouTube and Twitch streaming.

412
00:21:04,325 --> 00:21:04,946
They're cheap.

413
00:21:04,986 --> 00:21:06,887
They're not good for getting press.

414
00:21:07,788 --> 00:21:10,650
We're never going to get a proper publishing deal.

415
00:21:10,810 --> 00:21:12,051
We can't afford advertising.

416
00:21:12,071 --> 00:21:14,093
And even if we could, advertising almost never works.

417
00:21:14,333 --> 00:21:16,134
Word of mouth is all we ever got.

418
00:21:16,575 --> 00:21:18,516
And to be perfectly honest, you need

419
00:21:18,556 --> 00:21:19,797
to write a game that's good enough

420
00:21:19,857 --> 00:21:21,498
that someone's going to be passionate enough about it

421
00:21:21,538 --> 00:21:23,580
to bug their friends and talk on forums about it.

422
00:21:24,140 --> 00:21:26,862
If you don't have that, then you may have a problem.

423
00:21:28,143 --> 00:21:28,503
So anyway.

424
00:21:29,400 --> 00:21:33,020
This is what a game selling looked like in 2017.

425
00:21:33,100 --> 00:21:35,261
Thanks to luck and thanks to Fantasoft's kind help,

426
00:21:35,821 --> 00:21:39,442
we made $53,000 in today dollars in our first year.

427
00:21:39,462 --> 00:21:40,862
And that's solid money.

428
00:21:40,882 --> 00:21:41,902
That's a middle class income.

429
00:21:41,942 --> 00:21:43,183
For a grad student, that's amazing.

430
00:21:43,663 --> 00:21:46,583
And so I'm like, OK, this is for real.

431
00:21:47,143 --> 00:21:48,484
And the best thing about it, and I

432
00:21:48,504 --> 00:21:50,344
think one of the great miracles of being

433
00:21:50,364 --> 00:21:53,425
an indie creator in any field, is that I owned my work.

434
00:21:54,145 --> 00:21:56,126
When you make a video game, you've made a miracle.

435
00:21:56,146 --> 00:21:57,987
You've made a machine that prints money.

436
00:21:58,227 --> 00:21:59,648
Normally when you make a machine that prints money,

437
00:21:59,688 --> 00:22:01,089
it's a felony and they send you to jail,

438
00:22:01,109 --> 00:22:02,870
but here they let you get away with it.

439
00:22:03,351 --> 00:22:05,792
And even if that machine isn't making money right now,

440
00:22:05,872 --> 00:22:07,233
you wait five years, you remaster it,

441
00:22:07,253 --> 00:22:08,954
it might start, put some more ink in it,

442
00:22:08,974 --> 00:22:10,435
it might start kicking out money then.

443
00:22:11,296 --> 00:22:13,377
There has not hardly been a day gone by

444
00:22:13,477 --> 00:22:16,339
since I released Exile that I have not made money off of it.

445
00:22:16,979 --> 00:22:19,181
And owning your work is one of the greatest things

446
00:22:19,221 --> 00:22:19,581
in the world.

447
00:22:20,507 --> 00:22:22,668
And even back then I knew if I wanted to try to make a go of it,

448
00:22:23,008 --> 00:22:24,650
my whole story was going to be about two things,

449
00:22:24,750 --> 00:22:27,712
making a back catalog and getting myself some fans.

450
00:22:34,617 --> 00:22:38,299
So at this point, my grad school performance is pretty much non-existent.

451
00:22:38,379 --> 00:22:40,101
So I take a master's and I get the heck out.

452
00:22:41,221 --> 00:22:44,524
I port Exile to Windows, writing games on Windows 3.1.

453
00:22:44,564 --> 00:22:46,605
The less said about that, the better.

454
00:22:47,206 --> 00:22:51,389
It took me three days to draw one 256 color icon onto a screen.

455
00:22:51,409 --> 00:22:53,311
I put that demo on America Online.

456
00:22:53,371 --> 00:22:54,251
That sells, too.

457
00:22:54,792 --> 00:22:55,052
Great.

458
00:22:55,172 --> 00:22:56,293
So now I need to write another game.

459
00:22:56,473 --> 00:22:57,234
What am I going to do?

460
00:22:57,794 --> 00:22:58,975
Well, it's the computer game industry.

461
00:22:58,995 --> 00:23:02,057
I take the name of a previous game and I put a two after it.

462
00:23:04,679 --> 00:23:09,723
About this time, now everyone in this business is familiar with the phenomenon where your

463
00:23:09,743 --> 00:23:11,905
game sells great and then the sales suddenly drop by 90%.

464
00:23:13,296 --> 00:23:16,618
These days, in this unlightened, accelerated time, that usually takes about three days.

465
00:23:16,678 --> 00:23:18,019
Back then it took me a few months.

466
00:23:18,360 --> 00:23:23,404
But not long after I decided to go full-time, my cells just immediately fall into the toilet

467
00:23:23,504 --> 00:23:25,205
and I felt like I was going to die.

468
00:23:26,006 --> 00:23:31,910
I took that limitless terror and funneled that energy into working on Exile 2 harder.

469
00:23:33,031 --> 00:23:37,775
Now at this point, now I'm making a new game, all of a sudden the pattern for how I like

470
00:23:37,795 --> 00:23:39,457
to do things starts to be clearer.

471
00:23:40,098 --> 00:23:42,459
I tend to, I like a small company, I like to work alone.

472
00:23:42,739 --> 00:23:44,020
I keep doing that.

473
00:23:44,540 --> 00:23:46,801
Most of my code is functional, so I keep reusing it.

474
00:23:47,221 --> 00:23:50,582
I reuse most of my assets, most of my graphics, most of my sounds.

475
00:23:50,883 --> 00:23:53,323
I am merciless about reusing assets.

476
00:23:53,444 --> 00:23:56,645
I have used the same wolf icon in like 15 different games.

477
00:23:57,085 --> 00:23:58,646
If it's a decent icon, it looks like a wolf.

478
00:23:58,746 --> 00:24:00,406
The next game, it's still going to look like a wolf.

479
00:24:00,826 --> 00:24:05,988
People make fun of me for it all the time, but I am also still in business.

480
00:24:09,176 --> 00:24:13,242
release a new game, I look for the 25% of it that's the worst and I redo that.

481
00:24:13,682 --> 00:24:17,407
I am the leanest and the meanest of developers.

482
00:24:17,908 --> 00:24:20,932
And again, this is all part of finding my creative process.

483
00:24:20,972 --> 00:24:24,336
People make fun of me for it all the time, but it's still, it's just the way I work.

484
00:24:24,637 --> 00:24:25,518
