like an educational game, which is death. But it sold okay. And I was getting really

726
00:36:16,515 --> 00:36:18,336
sick of this point of everyone telling me

727
00:36:18,702 --> 00:36:21,122
your graphics suck, your graphics suck, your graphics suck.

728
00:36:21,142 --> 00:36:24,983
So I spent some actual money, I hired actual artists, and got graphics that were somewhere

729
00:36:25,023 --> 00:36:27,904
in the same continent as the standard for graphics at the time.

730
00:36:28,284 --> 00:36:32,305
The result, of course, was that every day people told me your graphics suck, your graphics

731
00:36:32,365 --> 00:36:33,246
suck, your graphics suck.

732
00:36:33,686 --> 00:36:36,607
That was the last time I ever made the mistake of making an effort.

733
00:36:40,508 --> 00:36:42,768
It's really important to note in indie games that...

734
00:36:43,467 --> 00:36:45,548
pretty much every game is going to be someone's favorite game.

735
00:36:45,788 --> 00:36:48,110
Your goal is to make a game that is enough people's favorite game

736
00:36:48,150 --> 00:36:50,511
to keep you in food and shelter.

737
00:36:50,931 --> 00:36:54,273
And this is why you should always be very scared of someone

738
00:36:54,453 --> 00:36:57,195
asking for more curation on a platform.

739
00:36:57,575 --> 00:37:00,157
Because one person or one panel of people

740
00:37:00,217 --> 00:37:03,199
can never, ever predict in the end what

741
00:37:03,239 --> 00:37:04,480
the market is going to like.

742
00:37:04,860 --> 00:37:08,222
The only thing that can decide what the market will like

743
00:37:08,662 --> 00:37:09,363
is the market.

744
00:37:12,094 --> 00:37:13,355
We'd been in this for a few years.

745
00:37:13,855 --> 00:37:15,136
Our games were selling consistently.

746
00:37:15,196 --> 00:37:16,456
We had a real fan base.

747
00:37:16,636 --> 00:37:18,797
Role-playing games are an evergreen niche,

748
00:37:18,817 --> 00:37:19,698
and we served it well.

749
00:37:20,078 --> 00:37:21,819
Everything seemed to be just cruising along fine.

750
00:37:22,099 --> 00:37:23,600
So that's when we almost went out of business.

751
00:37:27,261 --> 00:37:27,862
Suspense.

752
00:37:29,883 --> 00:37:31,483
Our next series was the Geneforge series,

753
00:37:31,503 --> 00:37:33,745
which I'm enormously proud of and is

754
00:37:34,405 --> 00:37:37,226
next in line for a really nice remastering.

755
00:37:37,586 --> 00:37:39,227
The Geneforge games were actually innovative.

756
00:37:40,037 --> 00:37:42,757
It was a sci-fi fantasy hybrid.

757
00:37:43,677 --> 00:37:45,057
There's no bad guys in GeneForge,

758
00:37:45,077 --> 00:37:46,958
there's just factions that you choose between.

759
00:37:47,038 --> 00:37:48,278
The gameplay is very open-ended.

760
00:37:48,318 --> 00:37:50,378
You can play an entirely pacifist character,

761
00:37:50,638 --> 00:37:52,059
get through the whole thing with trickery

762
00:37:52,079 --> 00:37:53,279
and never do a fight.

763
00:37:54,019 --> 00:37:57,060
At this point, the Exile games are embarrassingly old,

764
00:37:57,320 --> 00:38:00,020
so we start remastering them as Avernum games,

765
00:38:00,040 --> 00:38:02,000
and once again, those sell great.

766
00:38:03,041 --> 00:38:05,441
We hum along for another six years.

767
00:38:05,481 --> 00:38:08,141
We do two GeneForge games, we do two remasters,

768
00:38:08,181 --> 00:38:08,702
we have fans.

769
00:38:09,023 --> 00:38:11,505
Every year in November, we do a sale 10% off.

770
00:38:11,745 --> 00:38:12,686
Can you imagine?

771
00:38:13,006 --> 00:38:13,967
That always does really well.

772
00:38:15,308 --> 00:38:18,131
Around this time, we're making in the 200,000s a year

773
00:38:18,531 --> 00:38:19,912
for three full-time employees.

774
00:38:20,252 --> 00:38:22,194
And most of the time, that's around what we make.

775
00:38:22,394 --> 00:38:24,256
And that was pretty solid.

776
00:38:25,317 --> 00:38:28,600
So 2007, we've been doing this for about 13 years.

777
00:38:29,100 --> 00:38:30,962
I remastered Blades of Exile as Blades of Vernum.

778
00:38:30,982 --> 00:38:32,983
It has a really powerful scripting engine people

779
00:38:33,023 --> 00:38:34,545
can use to make scenarios.

780
00:38:34,725 --> 00:38:37,167
It takes forever to write it, and it's just too complicated.

781
00:38:37,207 --> 00:38:37,427
People.

782
00:38:38,122 --> 00:38:40,382
weren't really as into making adventures with it.

783
00:38:41,303 --> 00:38:43,804
I write Gene Forge 3, and quite frankly, I was lazy.

784
00:38:44,184 --> 00:38:45,504
I had been a long time as complacent.

785
00:38:45,564 --> 00:38:47,545
I slacked off, and I made a game that was just too similar

786
00:38:47,605 --> 00:38:48,745
to the two previous games.

787
00:38:50,006 --> 00:38:50,866
They just didn't do that well.

788
00:38:51,386 --> 00:38:52,307
They went down a bunch.

789
00:38:52,387 --> 00:38:54,507
And I'll just show you numbers to show what, for us,

790
00:38:54,588 --> 00:38:55,808
almost going out of business means.

791
00:38:56,328 --> 00:38:59,149
2003, we make almost $300,000 in today dollars.

792
00:38:59,429 --> 00:39:02,310
The next year, it's down by over a quarter.

793
00:39:02,948 --> 00:39:04,668
And again, three full-time employees.

794
00:39:04,848 --> 00:39:07,409
We have a ton of expenses doing the things

795
00:39:07,449 --> 00:39:08,489
that Steam does for us.

796
00:39:08,930 --> 00:39:10,910
And on top of that, we got two kids.

797
00:39:11,130 --> 00:39:12,611
And you know the joke, how much money

798
00:39:12,651 --> 00:39:13,751
does it take to raise kids?

799
00:39:14,251 --> 00:39:14,631
All of it.

800
00:39:15,472 --> 00:39:17,852
So this seems like a pretty healthy number.

801
00:39:18,012 --> 00:39:19,313
But this means we're bouncing checks.

802
00:39:19,533 --> 00:39:21,393
At this point, we're kind of running scared.

803
00:39:22,294 --> 00:39:25,094
And so at this point, I wise up and try

804
00:39:25,134 --> 00:39:27,215
to get over my complacency.

805
00:39:27,255 --> 00:39:29,756
I start redoing, redouble my energy

806
00:39:29,816 --> 00:39:31,176
and start redoing everything I can.

807
00:39:32,116 --> 00:39:32,537
And once again.

808
00:39:33,017 --> 00:39:36,038
Here's some advice that seems like sort of artsy,

809
00:39:36,498 --> 00:39:39,138
oh yeah, you always have to keep growing as a human man.

810
00:39:39,499 --> 00:39:41,039
Have you ever looked at your hands?

811
00:39:41,499 --> 00:39:41,719
No.

812
00:39:43,659 --> 00:39:45,120
You have to keep growing as an artist.

813
00:39:45,200 --> 00:39:46,860
And this is hard-nosed practical advice.

814
00:39:46,880 --> 00:39:49,401
Because remember, for the most part, we're toy makers.

815
00:39:49,861 --> 00:39:51,301
We sell amusements.

816
00:39:51,781 --> 00:39:53,982
We sell things that tickle people's brains.

817
00:39:54,062 --> 00:39:55,082
We sell surprise.

818
00:39:55,482 --> 00:39:58,303
And complacency and predictability and repetition

819
00:39:58,403 --> 00:39:59,503
are the death of that.

820
00:39:59,955 --> 00:40:02,618
If you want to write a sequel great sequels are awesome,

821
00:40:02,858 --> 00:40:04,780
but your sequel better introduce something new

822
00:40:05,121 --> 00:40:07,223
and it better introduce that new thing early

823
00:40:07,243 --> 00:40:09,065
because if people put up your game ago,

824
00:40:09,345 --> 00:40:11,628
yeah, I've done all this and I don't need to do more of this

825
00:40:12,128 --> 00:40:13,971
then you're going to start bouncing checks.

826
00:40:15,592 --> 00:40:17,915
We extend the Exile series into a vernum 4 5

827
00:40:18,215 --> 00:40:21,018
and 6 with a completely revamped engine that does really well.

828
00:40:21,941 --> 00:40:24,622
We redo a lot of stuff about how we do GeneForge 4.

829
00:40:24,742 --> 00:40:26,463
I expand the scripting engine and create

830
00:40:26,563 --> 00:40:28,604
really complicated multi-stage events

831
00:40:28,904 --> 00:40:31,025
and introduce them as soon as the game starts.

832
00:40:31,085 --> 00:40:32,946
The next two GeneForge games sell really well.

833
00:40:34,526 --> 00:40:37,407
And then the most surprising thing

834
00:40:37,427 --> 00:40:39,688
I could have possibly imagined happened.

835
00:40:40,469 --> 00:40:41,849
Indie games became big.

836
00:40:49,174 --> 00:40:52,115
Indie bubble is not really the correct term.

837
00:40:52,275 --> 00:40:54,115
It was not really a true speculative bubble.

838
00:40:54,435 --> 00:40:56,116
I should call it the indie glut.

839
00:40:56,836 --> 00:41:00,016
But I'm not going to go much into the factors that caused it.

840
00:41:00,037 --> 00:41:01,217
It's been much discussed.

841
00:41:01,357 --> 00:41:04,277
I will only add one factor about why indie games got big that I

842
00:41:04,297 --> 00:41:05,318
don't think gets enough attention.

843
00:41:06,178 --> 00:41:09,079
Indie games are successful because people like us.

844
00:41:09,879 --> 00:41:11,159
We're the little guy.

845
00:41:11,239 --> 00:41:14,540
We're the scrappy tinkerers in our garages fighting

846
00:41:14,600 --> 00:41:17,080
against the big monolithic corporations.

847
00:41:17,437 --> 00:41:22,160
This is an enormously powerful and moving archetype.

848
00:41:22,400 --> 00:41:24,142
Whole teen movies are made about this.

849
00:41:24,882 --> 00:41:30,046
And it is important to remember that we are likable,

850
00:41:30,146 --> 00:41:32,308
and it's important to concentrate on staying likable,

851
00:41:32,368 --> 00:41:35,070
because that likability is one of our greatest assets.

852
00:41:35,470 --> 00:41:39,173
If you're likable, that is what will make people stick with you

853
00:41:39,193 --> 00:41:40,534
through rough times, and that is what

854
00:41:41,755 --> 00:41:43,196
make people go to your Kickstarter and spend $1,000

855
00:41:43,236 --> 00:41:43,616
for a $15 game.

856
00:41:47,818 --> 00:41:49,139
Steam's big, indie games are big.

857
00:41:49,419 --> 00:41:51,980
I write a whole new game engine and a whole new game,

858
00:41:52,000 --> 00:41:54,502
which looks a little bit prettier, called Avidan.

859
00:41:55,803 --> 00:41:58,304
And between having a nice-looking new game

860
00:41:58,344 --> 00:41:59,965
and back catalog, we're able to make a lot of money.

861
00:42:00,606 --> 00:42:03,467
And I have to return again to the idea of luck.

862
00:42:03,988 --> 00:42:09,051
Now, at this point, I've been making indie games for decades.

863
00:42:10,292 --> 00:42:11,572
And I was sort of humming along.

864
00:42:11,612 --> 00:42:13,333
But all of a sudden, indie games became big

865
00:42:13,353 --> 00:42:15,074
when nobody was expecting it.

866
00:42:15,255 --> 00:42:17,036
There was a huge demand for product.

867
00:42:17,116 --> 00:42:17,456
And hey.

868
00:42:17,845 --> 00:42:20,186
I was sitting on years and years and years of back catalog.

869
00:42:20,466 --> 00:42:25,107
And as a result of that, I was able to get more deals and make more money than I in any

870
00:42:25,187 --> 00:42:26,528
remote way deserved.

871
00:42:28,268 --> 00:42:30,309
We got on all the fashionable online stores.

872
00:42:30,349 --> 00:42:31,669
We lucked into a meeting with Steam.

873
00:42:32,930 --> 00:42:36,131
And I'm sure a lot of people ask, Jeff Vogel, why did he get that detail?

874
00:42:36,151 --> 00:42:37,872
Why is he in that place?

875
00:42:37,892 --> 00:42:42,073
Well, one of the things is I always try to be the most frictionless person to work with.

876
00:42:42,613 --> 00:42:45,074
I'll negotiate about contracts, but not very much.

877
00:42:45,460 --> 00:42:49,703
I'm not a hard ass. I answer emails right away. I pay contractors right away.

878
00:42:49,943 --> 00:42:52,905
So when asked for assets, they have them in their hands by the end of the day.

879
00:42:53,225 --> 00:42:58,529
If you're as frictionless as possible to work with, you will be amazed at what opportunities it opens for you.

880
00:43:00,051 --> 00:43:03,873
We lower our games to $10 because Steam tells us that's what we have to do to be on Steam.

881
00:43:04,274 --> 00:43:07,016
We do so and God knows we made it up in volume.

882
00:43:07,856 --> 00:43:11,519
And at the beginning of the IndieGlitch, this is how much money we made.

883
00:43:12,119 --> 00:43:13,881
It is, again, this is

884
00:43:14,594 --> 00:43:21,756
life-changing money. It's just the culmination of a very lucky break, followed by a lot of

885
00:43:21,816 --> 00:43:28,638
work, and it's more than we deserve. The indie glut starts to rise. People see that indie

886
00:43:28,658 --> 00:43:31,939
games are big and they start writing them. We do our standard thing. We write two more

887
00:43:31,999 --> 00:43:35,941
new games. We write two more remasters. We make them as good as we could. We sell a ton.

888
00:43:36,401 --> 00:43:38,582
And then as more indie games flow in, we sell a lot less.

889
00:43:40,505 --> 00:43:43,026
Massive competition means we can't make up in volume anymore.

890
00:43:43,086 --> 00:43:45,547
We raise our prices to $20, which is where we are now.

891
00:43:46,347 --> 00:43:49,608
Indie development enters the recession period

892
00:43:49,948 --> 00:43:53,190
of its business cycle, a recession period

893
00:43:53,210 --> 00:43:55,971
that I suspect will probably last for a very long time,

894
00:43:56,031 --> 00:43:57,871
because it's tough to make a living as an artist.

895
00:44:00,432 --> 00:44:01,813
Other people are writing indie games now.

896
00:44:02,093 --> 00:44:02,833
It's a hot thing.

897
00:44:02,913 --> 00:44:04,134
It even gets to be in rooms.

898
00:44:05,554 --> 00:44:07,795
You all appear, and I quietly get old.

899
00:44:14,187 --> 00:44:18,369
I don't think anybody could have possibly imagined how big video games are going to get.

900
00:44:18,429 --> 00:44:22,010
It's over $100 billion a year, which is pretty big.

901
00:44:22,370 --> 00:44:24,171
And this is a vicious industry.

902
00:44:24,231 --> 00:44:27,212
This is a nasty, competitive, bloodsport industry.

903
00:44:27,492 --> 00:44:31,314
And as much as we hate to think about it, we are to some extent in this room all in

904
00:44:31,394 --> 00:44:32,515
competition with each other.

905
00:44:32,755 --> 00:44:34,736
There is only a finite number of Humble slots.

906
00:44:34,756 --> 00:44:37,097
There is only a finite number of Steam front page slots.

907
00:44:42,525 --> 00:44:43,645
It's a zero-sum game.

908
00:44:43,825 --> 00:44:45,806
If I get an opportunity, someone else doesn't.

909
00:44:46,226 --> 00:44:48,406
But it is fantastic, perhaps necessary,

910
00:44:48,446 --> 00:44:51,347
that still sometimes we can come here as a summit

911
00:44:51,367 --> 00:44:53,647
to genuinely try to help each other.

912
00:44:54,048 --> 00:44:55,408
Because we're artists, and God knows

913
00:44:55,468 --> 00:44:56,548
nobody else cares about us.

914
00:44:57,148 --> 00:44:58,369
It's one of the few things that makes

915
00:44:58,849 --> 00:44:59,889
life doing this tolerable.

916
00:45:01,029 --> 00:45:03,290
Month and a half ago, we came out with another remaster,

917
00:45:03,470 --> 00:45:04,830
Vernum 3 Ruined World.

918
00:45:05,090 --> 00:45:06,371
And it's doing quite well.

919
00:45:06,431 --> 00:45:07,691
It's not setting the world on fire,

920
00:45:07,711 --> 00:45:09,131
but we're going to be able to keep writing

921
00:45:09,151 --> 00:45:10,192
games for a couple more years.

922
00:45:10,944 --> 00:45:13,926
And I'm going to alternate between new games and remasters

923
00:45:14,066 --> 00:45:16,808
as long as I can handle it.

924
00:45:17,609 --> 00:45:19,890
And when I write a game, I'm making a whole new game

925
00:45:19,910 --> 00:45:21,311
right now and a whole new IP.

926
00:45:21,411 --> 00:45:25,294
And whenever I have a question, I follow the same north star

927
00:45:25,314 --> 00:45:26,354
that I always have.

928
00:45:27,155 --> 00:45:29,416
My process is I figure out what I want to play,

929
00:45:29,757 --> 00:45:30,577
and then I make that.

930
00:45:31,118 --> 00:45:35,120
And if my taste ever gets so bad that I fall out

931
00:45:35,140 --> 00:45:36,061
of line with the market.

932
00:45:36,403 --> 00:45:38,344
then I will receive my just punishment,

933
00:45:38,524 --> 00:45:40,704
and then I'll go write banking software or sell shoes.

934
00:45:42,464 --> 00:45:45,005
It helps that over the year, we have a big fan base.

935
00:45:45,045 --> 00:45:47,225
People drift out from being our fans for a decade

936
00:45:47,265 --> 00:45:48,386
and then float back.

937
00:45:48,886 --> 00:45:51,706
We have a long back catalog, which we mercilessly

938
00:45:51,786 --> 00:45:52,866
exploit whenever we can.

939
00:45:53,166 --> 00:45:54,387
And one of the great things is that never

940
00:45:54,427 --> 00:45:55,367
be ashamed of an old game.

941
00:45:55,387 --> 00:45:58,207
If a game's fun, 10 years later, it's still going to be fun.

942
00:45:58,627 --> 00:46:01,688
Never go to sleep on your old products.

943
00:46:01,768 --> 00:46:04,388
If you believed in it once, 10 years later,

944
00:46:04,588 --> 00:46:05,248
keep believing in it.

945
00:46:11,129 --> 00:46:13,210
But this is kind of the real question.

946
00:46:13,350 --> 00:46:16,911
I've told you a story about how I managed to live a life

947
00:46:16,991 --> 00:46:19,192
I dreamed of as a child and that a lot of people envy.

948
00:46:20,133 --> 00:46:20,933
Can you do it too?

949
00:46:21,473 --> 00:46:22,413
And that's the big question.

950
00:46:22,514 --> 00:46:25,535
And honestly, I have to believe that it is possible.

951
00:46:25,895 --> 00:46:28,696
If you write quality games consistently,

952
00:46:29,016 --> 00:46:31,037
if you're tenacious, if people like your games,

953
00:46:31,137 --> 00:46:32,117
if you build up a fan base,

954
00:46:32,157 --> 00:46:34,078
if you have the tenacity of the cockroach,

955
00:46:34,738 --> 00:46:40,020
then you will eventually make it, maybe.

956
00:46:41,657 --> 00:46:44,159
Making a living as an artist is hard.

957
00:46:44,399 --> 00:46:46,501
It's always been hard, and it always will be hard.

958
00:46:46,581 --> 00:46:48,103
And I want to say reassuring things,

959
00:46:48,123 --> 00:46:51,226
but I'm too fundamentally honest to not.

960
00:46:52,867 --> 00:46:54,429
I have to tell the truth.

961
00:46:54,509 --> 00:46:55,590
It's possible, but it's rough.

962
00:46:56,010 --> 00:46:57,371
And people ask all the time, do you

963
00:46:57,411 --> 00:46:59,793
think I have what it takes to make it?

964
00:46:59,854 --> 00:47:01,295
What do I need to do to make it?

965
00:47:01,955 --> 00:47:04,178
And my favorite quote about this comes

966
00:47:04,258 --> 00:47:07,861
from noted stand-up comedian and banjo enthusiast Steve Martin.

967
00:47:10,974 --> 00:47:15,337
You should always try to write games that pass the P test.

968
00:47:15,657 --> 00:47:18,439
You want to write a game that's so compelling that people

969
00:47:18,479 --> 00:47:19,319
forget to pee.

970
00:47:20,160 --> 00:47:22,141
If you let people test your game and you tell them you can't play it

971
00:47:22,161 --> 00:47:23,242
anymore, you should always be shooting.

972
00:47:23,282 --> 00:47:25,403
There should always be one person out of your testers,

973
00:47:25,563 --> 00:47:28,085
